<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1933-03-28T11:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1933-03-28T11:00:00-05:00" n="557" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d557">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">837.51/1551: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Cuba</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Guggenheim</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Habana</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-03-28T11:00:00-05:00">March 28, 1933—11
                                a.m.</date><lb/>[Received 12:50 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>26. My telegram No. 21, March 23, 4 p.m. Mortgage moratorium bill passed
                            by the Senate last night and prompt approval by the House of
                            Representatives is expected. Opinion regarding measure is very mixed.
                            Foreign banking interests are naturally very much opposed to it.</p>
                        <p>The Senate also passed a bill authorizing the President to arrange for a
                            delay in payments of amortization on Government debts both foreign and
                                internal.<note n="8" xml:id="d557fn8">The law, approved April 3,
                                1933, was published in the <hi rend="italic">Gaceta Oficial</hi>,
                                April 4, 1933.</note></p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Guggenheim</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>